##Chapter 7_5 Notes

##

Introduction

Chapter 7.5 — Entropy-Driven Cellular Automaton (ED-CA)
Introduction
This chapter introduces the Entropy-Driven Cellular Automaton (ED-CA), a discrete model extending the Relational Coherence Field Theory (RCFT) thermodynamic framework established in Chapters 7.1–7.4. Building on the entropy proof (S(β) = β [U(β) - F(β)], β_c = 0.39614 ± 0.0014), the ED-CA simulates stability and phase transitions within the critical β-band [0.3934, 0.3990]. A novel integration of Shard-polytope dynamics redefines cellular states as geometric polytopes, inspired by Positive Geometry’s encoding of scattering amplitudes and cosmological correlators. Initial tests with K=3 Shard-polytope interactions over 50 steps demonstrate coherent behavior, mapping entropy change (ΔS) to polytope volume change (ΔVolume = 0.014), with a baseline polytope volume of 1.237. However, monotonicity checks reveal fragility in low-order derivatives (n=1,2,4), necessitating further calibration.
A dynamic tuning parameter, κ, is introduced to optimize the acceptance probability (p_acc = Metropolis × G(β) × H(ΔVol_norm; κ)), leveraging a guard-aware Effective Sample Size (ESS) auto-selector. Initial mock results suggest κ = 5.0, but the coarse ΔS-ΔVol coupling and guard non-compliance outside the β-band highlight the need for an 8000-sweep validation. This extended run, confined to the β-band with derivatives sourced from Chapter 7.4 fits, aims to ensure complete monotonicity up to n=4, fitting α in ΔS = α · ΔVol (target corr ≥ 0.8), and refining κ for stability. The integration of these dynamics positions the ED-CA as a robust platform for testing RCFT’s geometric-thermodynamic bridge, with future extensions to multi-dimensional stability in Chapter 7.6.


##


